SIMPLE: twine
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Twine
<hw>Twine</hw> <pr>(tw⟦imac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>tw⟦imac⟧n</ets>, properly, a twisted or double thread; akin to D.
<ets>twijn</ets>, Icel. <ets>tvinni</ets>; from <ets>twi-</ets>. See
<er>Twice</er>, and cf. <er>Twin</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A twist;
a convolution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Typhon huge, ending in snaky <qex>twine</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A strong thread composed of two or three smaller
threads or strands twisted together, and used for various purposes, as
for binding small parcels, making nets, and the like; a small cord or
string.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act of twining or winding round.</def>
<rj><au>J. Philips.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Twine reeler</b></col>, <cd>a kind of machine for
twisting twine; a kind of mule, or spinning machine.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Twine
<hw>Twine</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Twined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Twining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>twinen</ets>, fr. AS.
<ets>tw⟦imac⟧n</ets> a twisted thread; akin to D. <ets>twijnen</ets> to
twine, Icel. & Sw. <ets>tvinna</ets>, Dan. <ets>tvinde</ets>. See
<er>Twine</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To twist together;
to form by twisting or winding of threads; to wreathe; <as>as, fine
<ex>twined</ex> linen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wind, as one thread around another, or as any
flexible substance around another body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let me <qex>twine</qex>⟦br⟧
Mine arms about that body.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wind about; to embrace; to entwine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let wreaths of triumph now my temples <qex>twine</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To change the direction of.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Fairfax.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To mingle; to mix.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Crashaw.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Twine
<hw>Twine</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To mutually twist
together; to become mutually involved.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wind; to bend; to make turns; to
meander.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As rivers, though they bend and <qex>twine</qex>,⟦br⟧
Still to the sea their course incline.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To turn round; to revolve.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To ascend in spiral lines about a support; to climb
spirally; <as>as, many plants <ex>twine</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twiner</ent>⟦br⟧
